This qualitative study explores high school refugee youth’s family support in&#13;
Newfoundland and Labrador. Data were collected from three high school teachers, three refugee&#13;
youth and two of their parents. The findings of this study reveal that many services on academic&#13;
assistance and social activities for refugee youth are available in the high school and local&#13;
communities. However, parent participants tend to depend entirely on local communities and&#13;
high school teachers in terms of their children’s academic studies due to language barriers and&#13;
low educational attainment. This study demonstrates that parents from diverse cultural&#13;
backgrounds have different perceptions on what constitutes quality education than those of&#13;
Canadian school teachers. More effort should be made to promote parent-teacher interaction by&#13;
schools and local communities.
